a that continues to shape policy immigration to this day. Using archival documents, examined through the lens of cultural sociology, this book reveals that the bureaucratic interpretations of immigration files emphasized not just economic utility, but also middle-class traits and values such as wealth accumulation, educational attainment, entrepreneurial spirit, resourcefulness, and a strong work ethic. By making "middle-class multiculturalism" a demographic reality and basis of nation-building in Canada, these state actors created an approach to managing racial diversity that at the onset was much-admired, but today, has generated significant social inequalities for immigrants and Canadian-born alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMiddle classzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMulticulturalismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aclass.  aeconomic immigration.  afamily immigration.  aimmigration bureaucrats.  aimmigration policy.  aintersectionality.  amiddle class.  amulticulturalism.  apolicy implementation.  arace.  aseasonal workers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107392200 cprintz978148752777840uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148752779240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487527792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487527792/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles